title: World's longest lasting cyclone, Cyclone Freddy, strikes Mozambique again
body:
Colmbo (News 1st) - Cyclone Freddy, the world's longest ever cyclone that is currently 35 days old and counting, on Sunday hit Mozambique for the second time.

Freddy has already killed 31 people whie sowing a trail of devastation across four countries - Madagascar and Mozabique twice each, Reunion, and Mauritius.

Freddy formed in the Timor Sea between Indonesia and Australia as a disturbance in late January and developed into a cyclone as it crossed the Indian Ocean and arrived off Africa.

It has been rated as a level 5, which is the strongest cyclone on the Safir-Simpson Scale that is used to measure the intensity of storms.

Up to now, the longest cyclone was Cyclone John in 1994 which lasted 31 days.

Freddy is also the cyclone with the highest Accumulated Cyclone Energy at a rating of 85.9, surpassing Cyclone Ioke's 83.6 in 2006.
source.title: Sri Lanka News - Newsfirst

title: Deadly cyclone Freddy wreaks havoc in Malawi | Sunday Observer
body:
At least 99 people have died in Malawi yesterday (13 march) due to Cyclone "Freddy" according to Country's Commissioner for Disaster Management Affairs of the country. Most damages was suffered Blantyre, the commercial hub of Malawi.

It is reported that another 134 people have been injured due to this cyclone. The total number casualties by the cyclone Freddy in Mozambique, Malawi and Madagascar since it first appeared last month about 136 up until now.

Guardian has reported that, Freddy is one of the strongest storms ever recorded in the southern hemisphere and could be the longest-lasting tropical cyclone, according to the World Meteorological Organization.
source.title: Sunday Observer
